      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid-convergence index (GCI) < 5% on primary QoI (shear stress integral) using at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "Three meshes (2.1 M, 6.4 M, 18.2 M cells) generated by uniform refinement ratio 1.41. GCI on area-averaged wall shear stress = 2.8%; GCI on RHI = 3.1%. Both below 5% threshold. Richardson extrapolation applied to report asymptotic solution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature) must be reproduced in simulation within ±5%.",
      "rationale": "In-vitro test conditions (Q = 5 L/min, N = 2500 rpm, T = 37 °C, glycerol-water analogue fluid) replicated in CFD boundary conditions. Fluid properties matched to within 2% of measured values. Pump casing geometry reconstructed from CMM survey data."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative validation metric (E_rms) on velocity magnitude < 10%; qualitative agreement on flow-feature topology.",
      "rationale": "E_rms on normalised velocity magnitude = 6.2% across all PIV measurement planes. Recirculation zone extent and impeller jet trajectory match PIV observations qualitatively. Pressure rise within 4% of measured characteristic curve across all five operating points."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (velocity, shear stress) must be mechanistically linked to the clinical endpoint (hemolysis).",
      "rationale": "Shear stress and exposure time are the primary mechanistic drivers of red-blood-cell damage in the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law model. Velocity field validation provides indirect confirmation of shear stress distribution. The RHI metric is directly derived from the validated QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
